5.3 Recovery Community Centers (RCCs)

RCCs are independent, non-profit organizations led and governed by representatives of the local recovery community. They are not treatment facilities but rather peer-operated hubs that provide a safe, welcoming, and substance-free environment. RCCs serve as a vital resource, connecting people to peer support, social activities, and practical resources like housing assistance, employment readiness, and skill-building workshops.47 They are a physical manifestation of the "Community" dimension of recovery, offering a place where hope lives.47

5.4 Digital Recovery Support

In an increasingly digital world, a variety of online tools have emerged to support recovery. These include smartphone applications and websites that offer 24/7 access to peer support, recovery resources, and coping skills exercises.50 Evidence-based apps like A-CHESS have been shown in clinical trials to reduce heavy drinking days and support long-term recovery.51 Other platforms like the Connections App provide moderated peer discussion groups and virtual support meetings.52 These digital tools are particularly valuable for individuals who face barriers to in-person care, such as those in rural areas or with transportation challenges, making support more accessible than ever before.51

Part III: A Directory of Recovery Resources in Nebraska

Navigating the landscape of addiction services can be daunting. This section provides a practical, state-specific directory of clinical treatment providers, community support networks, and specialized resources available to the residents of Nebraska.

Section 6: Navigating Nebraska's System of Care

The public behavioral health system in Nebraska is administered at both the state and local levels. Understanding this structure is the first step in accessing publicly funded services.

6.1 The Role of DHHS

The Nebraska Department of Health and Human Services (DHHS) Division of Behavioral Health (DBH) is the designated state authority for mental health and substance use disorders. The DBH is responsible for planning, funding, and providing oversight for a statewide, community-based system of prevention, treatment, and recovery support services.53

6.2 The Six Behavioral Health Regions

Nebraska's public behavioral health system is decentralized into six local units of government known as Behavioral Health Regions. These regions are responsible for planning services and contracting with local providers to meet the needs of their communities.57 To access services, individuals can contact their local regional authority directly:
Region 1 (Panhandle): (308) 635-3173 | http://region1bs.net
Region 2 (Southwest): (308) 534-0440 | www.r2hs.com
Region 3 (Central): (308) 237-5113 | www.Region3.net
Region 4 (Northern): (402) 370-3100 | www.region4bhs.org
Region 5 (Southeast): (402) 441-4343 | www.region5systems.net (This region includes Lancaster County).
Region 6 (Omaha Metro): (402) 444-6573 | www.regionsix.com (This region includes Douglas, Sarpy, Cass, Dodge, and Washington counties).57

6.3 Paying for Treatment in Nebraska

Cost should not be a barrier to receiving life-saving care. Nebraska offers several avenues for funding addiction treatment.
Medicaid (Heritage Health): Nebraska's Medicaid program provides comprehensive coverage for a wide range of medically necessary mental health and substance abuse services for both adults and children.59 Covered services include outpatient therapy, intensive outpatient programs (IOP), day treatment, residential care, and hospital services.60
State and Other Funding: For individuals who do not have insurance, funding may be available through the DHHS Division of Behavioral Health via the regional authorities.53 Many treatment centers also offer services on a sliding fee scale based on income or provide low-cost or free care, particularly non-profit organizations.63
The state's vision for a robust, integrated system of care is ambitious, as outlined in the DHHS strategic plan.66 However, this vision faces significant on-the-ground challenges, particularly in rural areas. A severe shortage of mental health professionals exists across the state, with 88 of 93 counties designated as professional shortage areas and 29 counties having no mental health provider at all.67 This disparity means that while the state aims to provide a full continuum of care, a rural resident may have to travel over an hour for therapy, creating a substantial barrier to accessing the "readily available" treatment that NIDA deems critical for success.10 This reality underscores the vital importance of statewide resources that transcend geography, such as telehealth services, digital recovery supports, and harm reduction initiatives like naloxone distribution, which serve as lifelines for Nebraskans in underserved communities.

