8.3 Sober Living Homes

Sober living homes, also called recovery residences, provide a crucial bridge between intensive treatment and independent living. They offer a structured, substance-free environment where residents can practice recovery skills while being supported by peers.97 The Oxford House model is a prominent example, consisting of a network of democratically run, self-supporting, and drug-free homes.99 Nebraska has a growing number of Oxford Houses for men and women. Other sober living options are often connected to treatment providers like Siena Francis House, The 1212 House, and Revive Ministries' Unity Houses.65

8.4 Support for Families and Friends

Addiction is a family disease. Support groups like Al-Anon (for friends and family of alcoholics) and Nar-Anon (for friends and family of narcotics users) provide a safe space for loved ones to share their experiences and learn healthy coping mechanisms.95 Many clinical providers, including Northpoint Nebraska and Lutheran Family Services, also offer specific family therapy and support programs.103

Section 9: Specialized and Local Resources

Beyond mainstream treatment and support groups, Nebraska has several specialized initiatives and local services that are vital to the recovery ecosystem.

9.1 Harm Reduction in Nebraska

Recognizing that not everyone is ready for abstinence, harm reduction services aim to keep people alive and reduce the negative consequences of drug use.
Naloxone (Narcan) Access: Naloxone is a life-saving medication that can reverse an opioid overdose. Through the state's STOPODNE (Stop Overdose Nebraska) initiative and a standing order issued by DHHS, naloxone is available at no cost and without a prescription at participating pharmacies across Nebraska.105 This is a critical public health measure to combat the rising number of opioid-related deaths.105

