Part IV: Hope and Action

The path of recovery is built on the foundational belief that a better life is possible. This final section aims to solidify that hope with real stories from Nebraskans and provide a clear, actionable plan for those ready to take the first step.

Section 10: Voices of Recovery in Nebraska

Statistics and directories provide the "what" and "where" of recovery, but personal stories provide the "why." They are powerful testaments to the principle of hope.
Nathan Wood's story exemplifies the transformative power of community support. Originally from Texas, he found himself homeless and struggling with severe alcohol use in Omaha. After being brought to the Siena Francis House, he was initially skeptical that recovery was possible for him, believing his addiction was a matter of weak willpower. Through the shelter's Miracles Addiction Recovery Program, he watched men just like him change their lives. After a personal low point—waking up in a truck on his 30th birthday in 14-degree weather—he finally committed to the program. Over five years later, Nathan is a sober graduate of the University of Nebraska at Omaha, working and thriving in the community he once felt lost in.119
Steve Martin, a career healthcare professional, shares his journey of recovering from a traumatic brain injury. After suffering repeated seizures and paralysis on his left side, he was fortunate to receive expert guidance that led him to QLI in Omaha for intensive rehabilitation. Within two months, he was back to work full-time. His story highlights the critical importance of timely access to appropriate, specialized care and underscores the work of organizations like the Brain Injury Association of Nebraska in connecting people with the resources they need to achieve maximum recovery.120
Testimonials from individuals who have attended centers like Northpoint Nebraska and Inroads to Recovery speak to the life-changing impact of compassionate, knowledgeable staff and the power of a supportive, sober community. Words like "This place has changed my life," "They gave me my life back," and "I couldn't imagine getting clean and sober anywhere else" echo the sentiment that connection and quality care are the cornerstones of healing.121
These stories, and countless others across Nebraska, demonstrate that no matter the circumstances, recovery is achievable with the right support.

Section 11: Your First Steps: Building a Personal Recovery Plan

For an individual or family member who has finished reading this guide and is wondering, "What do I do now?", here is a simple, actionable checklist to begin the journey.
Acknowledge the Need & Ensure Immediate Safety: The first step is recognizing that help is needed. If you or someone you know is in crisis, call the 988 Suicide & Crisis Lifeline or the Nebraska Family Helpline at (888) 866-8660.53 If there is a risk of opioid overdose, use the table in Section 9.1 to find a local pharmacy and obtain a free naloxone kit immediately.107
Get a Professional Assessment: Addiction is a complex medical condition. Contact a local treatment center (from Section 7) or your regional behavioral health authority (from Section 6.2) to schedule a comprehensive substance use evaluation. This is essential for creating an individualized treatment plan that matches your specific needs, as recommended by NIDA.10
Explore Payment Options: Do not let cost deter you. Call the number on the back of your insurance card or contact Nebraska Medicaid (Heritage Health) to understand your benefits.60 Ask providers directly about their payment options, including sliding fee scales or eligibility for state-funded assistance.53
Find Your Community: Connection is key. Use the meeting finder resources in Section 8 to find a peer support group that resonates with you. Try different types—AA, SMART Recovery, Refuge Recovery—online or in-person. The goal is to find a place where you feel understood and supported.
Involve Your Family (When Ready): Recovery is often more successful when loved ones are involved. Share the resources for families, like Al-Anon and Nar-Anon (from Section 8.4), with your support system. This helps them understand the disease of addiction and learn how to best support you.
Embrace Hope and Be Patient: Re-read the stories in Section 10. Remember that recovery is a non-linear process with ups and downs.1 There are many pathways to a better life. The journey begins with a single, courageous step.
